,"North German and Danish: variant of   Boye  .","Americanized form of French   Bois  ."]},{"name":"Bey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Abdullah, Dawoud, Fatima, Jamaal, Rasheedah, Shakoor, Zaib, Aisha, Akil, Ameen, Aminah.","North German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Beye</i> or <i>Baye</i>, vowel variants of   Boye  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Baj</b>: nickname or occupational name from Upper Sorbian <i>baj</i> ‘storyteller’. Compare   Bay  ."]},{"name":"Boje","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Goetz, Johannes.","German: variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boyens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Georg.","North German and North Frisian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans Peter, Heinz, Horst.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Boie</i>, which may be from ancient Germanic <i>Boio</i> (see   Boye   1 and 2) or an Old English <i>Boia</i>. The latter is common as a first element in English placenames, and is difficult to tell apart from the ordinary word <i>boy</i>, to which it may be related.","English: from Middle English <i>boy</i> ‘young man, servant’, also ‘knave’ or ‘rogue’. Compare   Ladd  ."]},{"name":"Boykins","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch <b>Boeijkens</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Boye   with the diminutive element <i>-ken</i> and genitive <i>-s</i>. Compare the English cognate   Boykin   and North German   Boyken  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Grace’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ferte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Cohen, Hyman, Isadore.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): nickname from Yiddish <i>fertl</i> ‘aquarter’; perhaps applied to a very small person."],"variants":[{"name":"Fertal","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Fearghal ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marie de la Ferte de Boye was born about 1274, in Roye, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France as the daughter of Matthieu De Roye III and Jeanne de Vendeuil. She had at least 1 son. She died on 3 April 1340, in La Ferté-Bernard, Sarthe, France, at the age of 67."},"et":{"Abt 1274–3 April 1340":"umbes 1274–3. aprill 1340","1274–1340":"1274–1340","1277–1349":"1277–1349","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1305–1348":"1305–1348","1262–1350":"1262–1350","–1295":"–1